Final Project: Submission¶

By Ethan Nguonly, Mohamed Sondo, and Brian Truong¶

Intro¶

HR analytics is a field that continues to grow and one very important metric of interest is employee atrition. Attrition is the rate at which employees leave a company, usually for a variety of reasons. The goal of this project is to analyze a dataset of employees and whether they left the company or not. The dataset that we are working with is 2019 HR Employee Attrition from Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/james2919/hr-employee-attrition). If we are able to successfully model the key predictors of employee attrition, companies will be able to better target and retain talent, thus reducing the need to hire and retrain new employees.

McCurr Healthcare Consultancy is an MNC that has thousands of employees spread out across the globe. The company believes in hiring the best talent available and retaining them for as long as possible. A huge amount of resources is spent on retaining existing employees through various initiatives. The Head of People Operations wants to bring down the cost of retaining employees. For this, he proposes limiting the incentives to only those employees who are at risk of attrition We have been asked to identify patterns in characteristics of employees who leave the organization. Also, We have to use this information to predict if an employee is at risk of attrition. This information will be used to target them with incentives.

Objective:¶

  • To identify the different factors that drive attrition
  • To make a model to predict the attrition

Dataset:Description of data source¶

The data source used for this project can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/james2919/hr-employee-attrition

It has the following features:

  • EmployeeNumber (Int) - Employee Identifier
  • Attrition (String) - Did the employee attrite?
    • "Yes"
    • "No"

Demographic

  • Age - Age of the employee
  • Education (Int)
    • 1 - Below College
    • 2 - CollegeBachelor
    • 4 - Master
    • 5 - Doctor
  • EducationField (String) - Field of Education
    • "Life Sciences"
    • "Other"
    • "Medical"
    • "Marketing"
    • "Technical Degree"
    • "Human Resources"
  • Gender (String)
    • "Male"
    • "Female"
  • MaritalStatus (String)
    • "Single"
    • "Married"
    • "Divorced"
  • NumCompaniesWorked (Int) - Number of companies worked at
  • Over18 (String) - Over 18 years of age?
    • "Y"
    • "N" There are no N values in the dataset

Compensation

  • MonthlyIncome (Int) - Monthly Salary
  • PercentSalaryHike (Int) - The percentage increase in salary last year
  • StockOptionLevel (Int) - Stock Option Level

Unknown what these actually represent

  • HourlyRate (Int) - Data description not available**
  • DailyRate (Int) - Data description not available**
  • MonthlyRate (Int) - Data description not available**

Position information

  • BusinessTravel (String) - Travel commitments for the job
    • "Non-Travel"
    • "Travel_Rarely"
    • "Travel_Frequently"
  • Department (String) - Employee Department
    • "Sales"
    • "Research & Development"
    • "Human Resources"
  • DistanceFromHome (Int) - Distance from work to home (in km)
  • JobInvolvement (Int)
    • 1 - Low
    • 2 - Medium
    • 3 - High
    • 4 - Very High
  • JobLevel (Int) - Level of job (1 to 5)
  • JobRole (String) - Job Roles
    • "Sales Executive"
    • "Research Scientist"
    • "Laboratory Technician"
    • "Manufacturing Director"
    • "Healthcare Representative"
    • "Manager"
    • "Sales Representative"
    • "Research Director"
    • "Human Resources"
  • StandardHours (Int) - Standard Hours All of these are 80
  • OverTime (String)
    • "Yes"
    • "No"

History with company

  • PerformanceRating (Int)
    • 1 - Low
    • 2 - Good
    • 3 - Excellent
    • 4 - Outstanding
  • TrainingTimesLastYear (Int) - Number of training attended last year
  • TotalWorkingYears (Int) - Total years worked
  • YearsAtCompany (Int) - Years at Company
  • YearsInCurrentRole (Int) - Years in the current role
  • YearsSinceLastPromotion (Int) - Years since the last promotion
  • YearsWithCurrManager (Int) - Years with the current manager

Job satisfaction

  • EnvironmentSatisfaction (Int)
  • JobSatisfaction (Int)
  • WorkLifeBalance (Int
  • RelationshipSatisfaction (Int)
    • 1 - Low
    • 2 - Medium
    • 3 - High
    • 4 - Very High

Objective :¶

  • To identify the different factors that drive attrition

  • To make a model to predict if an employee will attrite or not

  • The company want the Recall to be maximized, the greater the Recall, the higher the chances of minimizing false negatives. Hence, the focus should be on increasing Recall (minimizing the false negatives) or in other words identifying the true positives (i.e. Class 1) very well, so that the company can provide incentives to control attrition rate especially for top-performers. This would help in optimizing the overall project cost towards retaining the best talent.

Observations:

  • The age distribution is close to a normal distribution with the majority of employees between the ages of 25 and 50.

  • The percentage salary hike is skewed to the right, which means employees are mostly getting lower percentage salary increases.

  • MonthlyIncome and TotalWorkingYears are skewed to the right, indicating that the majority of workers are in entry / mid-level positions in the organization.

  • DistanceFromHome also has a right skewed distribution, meaning most employees live close to work but there are a few that live further away.

  • On average, an employee has worked at 2.5 companies. Most employees have worked at only 1 company.

  • The YearsAtCompany variable distribution shows a good proportion of workers with 10+ years, indicating a significant number of loyal employees at the organization.

  • The YearsInCurrentRole distribution has three peaks at 0, 2, and 7. There are a few employees that have even stayed in the same role for 15 years and more.

  • The YearsSinceLastPromotion variable distribution indicates that some employees have not received a promotion in 10-15 years and are still working in the organization. These employees are assumed to be high work-experience employees in upper-management roles, such as co-founders, C-suite employees etc.

  • The distributions of DailyRate, HourlyRate and MonthlyRate appear to be uniform and do not provide much information. It could be that daily rate refers to the income earned per extra day worked while hourly rate could refer to the same concept applied for extra hours worked per day. Since these rates tend to be broadly similar for multiple employees in the same department, that explains the uniform distribution they show.

for i in cat_cols:

        (pd.crosstab(df[i],df['Attrition'],normalize='index')*100).plot(kind='bar',figsize=(8,4),stacked=True)
        plt.ylabel('Percentage Attrition %')

Observations:

  • Employees working overtime have more than a 30% chance of attrition, which is very high compared to the 10% chance of attrition for employees who do not work extra hours.
  • As seen earlier, the majority of employees work for the R&D department. The chance of attrition there is ~15%
  • Employees working as sales representatives have an attrition rate of around 40% while HRs and Technicians have an attrition rate of around 25%. The sales and HR departments have higher attrition rates in comparison to an academic department like Research & Development, an observation that makes intuitive sense keeping in mind the differences in those job profiles. The high-pressure and incentive-based nature of Sales and Marketing roles may be contributing to their higher attrition rates.
  • The lower the employee's job involvement, the higher their attrition chances appear to be, with 1-rated JobInvolvement employees attriting at 35%. The reason for this could be that employees with lower job involvement might feel left out or less valued and have already started to explore new options, leading to a higher attrition rate.
  • Employees at a lower job level also attrite more, with 1-rated JobLevel employees showing a nearly 25% chance of attrition. These may be young employees who tend to explore more options in the initial stages of their careers.
  • A low work-life balance rating clearly leads employees to attrite; 30% of those in the 1-rated category show attrition.

Additional Feature Selection Techniques¶

In [16]:
# dropping the columns
pca_df=pca_df.drop(['EmployeeNumber','Over18','StandardHours'],axis=1)

# convert categorical variables to numbers
pca_df['Attrition'] = pca_df['Attrition'].map({"No": 0, "Yes": 1})
pca_df['EducationField'] = pca_df['EducationField'].map({"Life Sciences": 0, "Other": 1, "Medical": 2, 
                                                  "Marketing": 3, "Technical Degree": 4, "Human Resources": 5})
pca_df["Gender"] = pca_df["Gender"].map({"Male": 0, "Female": 1})
pca_df["MaritalStatus"] = pca_df["MaritalStatus"].map({"Single": 0, "Married": 1, "Divorced": 2})
pca_df["BusinessTravel"] = pca_df["BusinessTravel"].map({"Non-Travel": 0, "Travel_Rarely": 1, "Travel_Frequently": 2})
pca_df["Department"] = pca_df["Department"].map({"Sales": 0, "Research & Development": 1, "Human Resources": 2})
pca_df["JobRole"] = pca_df["JobRole"].map({"Sales Executive": 0, "Research Scientist": 1, "Laboratory Technician": 2,
                                   "Manufacturing Director": 3, "Healthcare Representative": 4, "Manager": 5,
                                   "Sales Representative": 6, "Research Director": 7, "Human Resources": 8})
pca_df['OverTime'] = pca_df['OverTime'].map({"No": 0, "Yes": 1})

# format dataframe values for feature selection
feature_names = pca_df.columns[1:]
array = pca_df.values
X = array[:,1:len(pca_df.columns)]
Y = array[:,0]
Y = Y.astype('int')

Feature Selection Observations¶

Based on the various feature selection techniques, we were able to gain further insight into which variables have the highest impact on employee attrition. Namely, through feature selection with univariate statistical tests, it was found that the top four factors for attrition were 'OverTime', 'TotalWorkingYears', 'JobLevel', 'MaritalStatus'. Through feature extraction with RFE, we found that 'BusinessTravel', 'JobInvolvement', 'MaritalStatus', 'OverTime' most greatly impacted attrition. Lastly, through Extra Trees Classifier, we found that 'OverTime', 'Age', 'TotalWorkingYears', 'MonthlyIncome' had the greates impacts. Common factors between these feature selections techniques included "Overtime", "MaritialStatus", and "TotalWorkingYears", so it is important for us to include all of these parameters as predictors in our model.

  1. Prepare data for modeling

Scaling the data¶

The independent variables in this dataset have different scales. When features have different scales from each other, there is a chance that a higher weightage will be given to features that have a higher magnitude, and they will dominate over other features whose magnitude changes may be smaller but whose percentage changes may be just as significant or even larger. This will impact the performance of our machine learning algorithm, and we do not want our algorithm to be biased towards one feature.

The solution to this issue is Feature Scaling, i.e. scaling the dataset so as to give every transformed variable a comparable scale.

I will use the Standard Scaler method, which centers and scales the dataset using the Z-Score.

It standardizes features by subtracting the mean and scaling it to have unit variance.

The standard score of a sample x is calculated as:

z = (x - u) / s

where u is the mean of the training samples (zero) and s is the standard deviation of the training samples.

Model evaluation criterion¶

The model can make two types of wrong predictions:¶

  1. Predicting an employee will attrite when the employee doesn't attrite
  2. Predicting an employee will not attrite and the employee actually attrites

Which case is more important?¶

  • Predicting that the employee will not attrite but the employee attrites i.e. losing out on a valuable employee or asset. This would be considered a major miss for any employee attrition predictor, and is hence the more important case of wrong predictions.

How reduce False Negatives?¶

  • The company would want the Recall to be maximized, the greater the Recall, the higher the chances of minimizing false negatives. Hence, the focus should be on increasing Recall (minimizing the false negatives) or in other words identifying the true positives (i.e. Class 1) very well, so that the company can provide incentives to control attrition rate especially for top-performers. This would help in optimizing the overall project cost towards retaining the best talent.

A function to calculate and print the classification report and confusion matrix so that we don't have to rewrite the same code repeatedly for each model.¶

#creating metric function that can be called for eeach model
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels=['Not Attrite', 'Attrite'], yticklabels=['Not Attrite', 'Attrite'])
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

    logistic_regression.fit(x_train, y_train)
    y_pred = logistic_regression.predict(x_test)

    cols = x_train.columns
    coef_lg=logistic_regression.coef_
    return pd.DataFrame(coef_lg,columns=cols).T.sort_values(by=0,ascending=False)

K-Nearest Neighbors¶

Another simple classifier that can be applied to this data set is the K-Nearest Neighbors model. Compared with logistic regression, it is not as straight forward to find the effect of various features, especially with higher dimensional inputs. While K-NN also cannot handle the categorical features out of the box, K-NN similarly handle them by converting the n members of a categorical feature into n binary features.

In [33]:
class Model(object):
    '''
    Harness for training and evaluating models
    
    Author: Brian Truong
    '''

    def __init__(self, title, model, features, labels, test_partition_pct=0.3):
        '''
        @param title:              Title of the model
        @param model:              Model instance to use
        @param features:           Input features to use
        @param labels:             Output labels to use
        @param test_partition_pct: Percentage of the given data to use for testing
        '''

        self.title = title
        self.instance = model
        self.features = features
        self.labels = labels

        self.train_data, self.test_data, self.train_labels, self.test_labels = train_test_split(
            features,
            labels,
            test_size=test_partition_pct,
            random_state=1,
            stratify=labels
        )

    def evaluate(self):
        '''Fit and evaluate the model'''

        print(f'\n{"-" * 10} {self.title}\n')

        print(f'Features: {self.features.shape[1]}')
        print(f'Train data: {len(self.train_labels)}; Attrition: {np.sum(self.train_labels)}')
        print(f'Test data: {len(self.test_labels)}; Attrition: {np.sum(self.test_labels)}')

        # Run model
        self.instance.fit(self.train_data, self.train_labels)
        print(f'\nModel hyperparameters:\n{json.dumps(self.instance.get_params(), indent=4)}')
        print(f'\nModel accuracy: {self.instance.score(self.test_data, self.test_labels)}\n')
        
        # Generate confusion matrix
        predictions = self.instance.predict(self.test_data)
        metrics_score(self.test_labels, predictions)
        
    def get_features_correlation(self):
        '''Get the features correlation matrix'''

        correlation = np.abs(self.features.corr())
        return correlation.style.background_gradient(cmap='coolwarm')

    def display_roc_curve(self, ax=None):
        '''
        Display the precision recall curve

        @param ax: (Optional) Matplotlib axis object to plot with
        '''

        axis = ax
        if not axis:
            _, axis = plt.subplots()

        probabilities = self.instance.predict_proba(self.test_data)[:, 1]
        false_pos_rate, true_pos_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(self.test_labels, probabilities)

        axis.plot(false_pos_rate, true_pos_rate, color='orange', label='ROC')
        axis.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--')
        axis.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')
        axis.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')
        axis.set_title(f'{self.title}: ROC curve')

    def get_grid_search_results(self, search_params, top=10):
        '''
        Pretty print the GridSearchCV results, and return the best params

        @param search_params: Dictionary of hyperparameter values to search with
        @param top:           (Optional) Number of top configurations to display

        @return: Best paramters
        '''
        model = GridSearchCV(self.instance, search_params, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
        model.fit(self.train_data, self.train_labels)

        print(f'Best params: {model.best_params_}\nTop {top} configurations:')

        accuracies = pd.DataFrame(model.cv_results_)\
                       .filter(regex='(^param_)|mean_test_score',axis=1)\
                       .nlargest(top, columns=['mean_test_score'])
        display(accuracies)

        return model.best_params_

    def display_feature_importance(self):
        '''
        Plot the feature importance.
        ONLY WORKS FOR DECISION TREES.
        '''

        importances = pd.DataFrame(
            self.instance.feature_importances_,
            index=self.test_data.columns,
            columns=['Importance']
        ).sort_values(by='Importance',ascending=False)

        plt.figure(figsize=(13,13))
        sns.barplot(importances.Importance,importances.index)


def scatterplot_features(feature_a, feature_b, ax=None):
    '''
    Plot a scatterplot between two features

    @param feature_a: Feature to use as x-axis
    @param feature_b: Feature to use as y-axis
    @param ax: (Optional) Matplotlib axis object to plot with
    '''

    axis = ax
    if not axis:
        _, axis = plt.subplots()

    axis.scatter(
        df[feature_a][df['Attrition'] == 0],
        df[feature_b][df['Attrition'] == 0],
        marker='D',
        label='No'
    )
    axis.scatter(
        df[feature_a][df['Attrition'] == 1],
        df[feature_b][df['Attrition'] == 1],
        color='orange',
        label='Yes')

    axis.set_xlabel(feature_a)
    axis.set_ylabel(feature_b)
    axis.legend()

For the second K-NN model, a small feature set was chosen based on intuition: TotalWorkingYears, MonthlyIncome, and JobLevel. Using a smaller feature allows for better computational performance, and are a bit easier to decipher.

This is based on an idea that attrition is a factor of professionals changing companies to grow their career, with TotalWorkingYears indicating the stage in their career, JobLevel the responsibilities expected, and MonthlyIncome the compensation. Looking at the scatter plots below, attritioning employees tend to cluster towards the bottom left of the plots, indicating that younger, lower paid, lower level employees attrite. However, non-attritioned employees seem to be distributed fairly evenly, so there are no clear cut clusters of different classes.

Tuning hyperparameters with GridSearchCV¶

Taking the full model and tuning the hyperparameters with grid search cross-validation results in a slight increase in performance, from ~0.953 to ~0.964. For this model, best parameters turned out to be increasing n=6 to n=9.

def grid_search_knn_all():
    # Tuning KNN using all features
    knn_full = Model(
        title='K-NN All tuned',
        model=KNeighborsClassifier(),

        labels=Y

    best_params = knn_full.get_grid_search_results({

Decision Trees¶

Another fairly simple model to explore for the baseline are decision trees. Compared with K-NN, decision trees allow for a transparent look into the inner workings of the model. However, this is quickly lost as the tree is prone to becoming large and overly complex. For instance, take the below decision tree using the same reduced feature set as the second K-NN, splitting on the best Gini index, or how likely a random sampling would choose the incorrect class.

With a decreased performance in comparison to the K-NN of ~0.941, it uses a relatively complex tree to do so, with a maximum depth of 17 levels and 192 leaf nodes.

Tuning hyperparameters with GridSearchCV¶

Another way to reduce complexity is to choose a cost complexity alpha value to incentize trees towards a more simpler represention. After selecting a number of promising alphas, a general cross-validation grid search was done to find the to tune the other decision tree hyperparameters. As it turns out, given the reduced feature set, the default tuning 0 pruning alpha is the most optimal, while using an entropy based criterion and a random splitter results in a slight bump in accuracy, from ~0.94 to ~0.95, comparable to the K-NN model.

In [46]:
def tree_tuned_hyperparameters():
    # Tuning decision tree with reduced features
    tree_reduced = Model(
        title='Decision Tree Reduced Tuned',
        model=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0),
        features=X_scaled,
        labels=Y
    )

    # Find the best cost complexity pruning alpha values
    path = tree_reduced.instance.cost_complexity_pruning_path(
        tree_reduced.train_data,
        tree_reduced.train_labels
    )

    table = {
        'accuracy': [],
        'ccp_alpha': path.ccp_alphas
    }

    for ccp_alpha in path.ccp_alphas:
        tree = Model(
            title='Decision Tree Reduced Tuned',
            model=DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha, random_state=0),
            features=X_scaled,
            labels=Y
        )
        accuracy = tree.instance.fit(tree.train_data, tree.train_labels)\
                                .score(tree.test_data, tree.test_labels)
        table['accuracy'].append(accuracy)

    top = 10
    table_best = pd.DataFrame(table).nlargest(top, columns=['accuracy'])
    print(f'Top {top} cost complexity alphas')
    display(table_best)

    # Do a grid search on the top values
    best_params = tree_reduced.get_grid_search_results({
        'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
        'splitter': ['best', 'random'],
        'ccp_alpha': table_best['ccp_alpha'].values
    })

    # Evaluate the best parameters
    tree_reduced.instance.set_params(**best_params)
    tree_reduced.evaluate()
    print(f'\nTree depth: {tree_reduced.instance.get_depth()}\nTree leaves: {tree_reduced.instance.get_n_leaves()}')
    tree_reduced.display_roc_curve()

Building the Random Forest Classifier¶

Random Forest is a bagging algorithm where the base models are Decision Trees. Samples are taken from the training data and on each sample a decision tree makes a prediction.

The results from all the decision trees are combined together and the final prediction is made using voting or averaging.

In [ ]:

  • Other features such as job satisfaction, environment satisfaction and their job level also play a crucial role in knowing whether an employee will attrite or not.

Tuning the Random Forest¶

n_estimators: The number of trees in the forest.

min_samples_split: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node:

min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node.

max_features{auto, sqrt, log2, 'None'}: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split.

  • If auto, then max_features=sqrt(n_features).

  • If sqrt, then max_features=sqrt(n_features) (same as auto).

  • If log2, then max_features=log2(n_features).

  • If None, then max_features=n_features.

Conclusion¶

  • The best model we have got so far is the tuned random forest model which is giving nearly ~85% recall on the test data .
  • The company should use this model to know beforehand which employee is going to attrite and act accordingly.
  • Overtime, MonthlyIncome, DailyRate, number of companies worked and work experience/age seem to be the most important features.

Recommendations¶

  • Working overtime is the most important driver of attrition. The organization should manage their work more efficiently so that employees don't have to work overtime and can manage to have a work-life balance, or failing this, the company could provide some additional incentives to employees who are working overtime in order to retain them.
  • A higher monthly income might lower the odds of an employee attriting. The company should make sure that all its employees are compensated at least based on industry standards.
  • As observed earlier, the organization has a lower percentage salary hike and promotions are given less frequently. The company might be able to focus on giving promotions more frequently or they could increase the annual appraisal hike to incentivize employees to stay.
  • The organization could come up with a revised CTC plan with stock options for the employees in order to keep them motivated and invested in the company's performance.
  • The organization should also modify its hiring policy as people who have worked in many companies and have switched a lot should not be hired very often.
  • Distance from home is also an important factor for attrition - employees traveling a larger distance to reach the workplace are the ones attriting. For such employees, the company can provide cab facilities so that the commute of employees gets easier.
  • The company should also keep track of the hourly rate or the daily rate, so that when the employees need to stay overtime for extra work they are well compensated for that.
  • The organization should focus on improving the culture and environment at the workplace by coming up with new ideas to make the environment more open and friendly.
  • Keeping track of the problems which employees with lesser experience face and how the management can help them, will create a healthy environment for the young employees.
  • The organization should also focus on the employees who are working in sales and marketing, as attrition rate is quite high for these departments. Perhaps the company could look into their incentive schemes and try to come up with new incentive methods to motivate them to stay.
